				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Bas=
al organ  of a vascular plant</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the part of a plant. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Root=
 (disambiguation)">Root (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
"Rooted" redirects here. For the 1969 play and TV movie adaptation, see <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rooted_(film)" title=3D"Rooted (film)=
">Rooted (film)</a>. For the song, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Ciara_discography" title=3D"Ciara discography">Ciara discography</a>.<=
/div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Primary_and_secondary_cotton_roots.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/a/ab/Primary_and_secondary_cotton_roots.jpg/250px-Primary_an=
d_secondary_cotton_roots.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"18=
8" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"360" data-file-height=3D"27=
0"></a><figcaption>Primary and secondary roots in a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cotton" title=3D"Cotton">cotton</a> plant</figcaption></f=
igure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vascular_plant" title=3D"Vas=
cular plant">vascular plants</a>, the <b>roots</b> are the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plant_organ" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plant =
organ">organs of a plant</a> that are modified to provide anchorage for the=
 plant and take in water and nutrients into the plant body, which allows pl=
ants to grow taller and faster.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stevens2019_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Stev=
ens2019-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> They are most often below the surface of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil" title=3D"Soil">soil</a>, but roots =
can also be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerial_root" title=3D"=
Aerial root">aerial</a> or aerating, that is, growing up above the ground o=
r especially above water.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Function">Function</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Function"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Roots perform several essential and specialised roles that support plant=
 growth, development and survival. Their <b>primary functions</b> are ancho=
rage, uptake (absorption) of water and dissolved minerals, and conduction o=
f these resources to the shoot. Beyond these, roots carry out a range of im=
portant <b>secondary</b> and <b>adaptive functions</b> =E2=80=94 storage of=
 reserves, synthesis of growth regulators, gas exchange in waterlogged envi=
ronments, facilitation of symbiotic nutrient acquisition, and vegetative pr=
opagation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Primary_functions">Primary =
functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRo=
ot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Primary functi=
ons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p><b>Anchorage and mechanical support.</b> Roots fix the plant in the subs=
trate and resist mechanical forces (wind, waterflow); vigorous root systems=
 are essential for crop stability and prevention of lodging.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Zeiger_Taiz_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Root#cite_note-Zeiger_Taiz-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-5">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p><b>Absorption of water and mineral nutrients.</b> Root epidermal cel=
ls and root hairs take up soil water and dissolved ions; these are then con=
ducted to the shoot via the xylem. Root architecture (depth, spread) determ=
ines access to water and nutrients in different soil horizons.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root=
#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Secondary_and_specialised_f=
unctions">Secondary and specialised functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Secondary and specialised functions"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><b>Storage of reserve food and water.</b> Many roots (fleshy taproots, t=
uberous roots) accumulate carbohydrates and water that support perennial gr=
owth or regrowth after dormancy. Examples include sweet potato and carrot.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Root#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Conduction.</b> Roots conduct absorbed water, minerals and some s=
ynthesised compounds to the shoot via vascular tissues (xylem and phloem co=
nnections).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Zeiger_Taiz_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Zeiger_Taiz-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Synthesis of growth regulators.</b> Roots synthesise and modulate=
 plant hormones (e.g., cytokinins, some auxin metabolism), influencing shoo=
t development and whole-plant physiology.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-9"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p><b>Aeration and gas exchange (in aquatic/waterlogged soils).</b> Spe=
cialised structures (pneumatophores, aerial roots) permit gas exchange wher=
e soil oxygen is limited, enabling respiration in mangroves and other hydro=
phytes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Symbiotic interactions and enhanced nutrient uptake.</b> Roots fo=
rm mutualisms (e.g., mycorrhizae, nitrogen-fixing nodules) that greatly inc=
rease nutrient acquisition and stress tolerance. These associations remodel=
 root architecture and function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-11"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Mechanical adaptations and additional support.</b> Adventitious a=
nd brace/prop roots (e.g., maize, some mangroves, banyan) provide extra sup=
port, anchorage and stability in particular environments.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cit=
e_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Vegetative propagation.</b> Adventitious rooting on stems, nodes =
or cuttings allows many species to reproduce asexually and to regenerate af=
ter damage; this is widely exploited in horticulture.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_no=
te-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Notes">Notes</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Many functions overlap: a given root can simultaneously anchor, absorb, =
store reserves and engage in symbiosis. Root form and function are plastic =
and shaped by species genetics and environmental context (soil texture, wat=
er availability, aeration and mechanical stresses).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_roots_(major_rooti=
ng_system)"><span id=3D"Types_of_roots_.28major_rooting_system.29"></span>T=
ypes of roots (major rooting system)</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"E=
dit section: Types of roots (major rooting system)"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Plants produce a variety of root systems that differ in origin, structur=
e and function (anchorage, absorption, storage, aeration and vegetative pro=
pagation). The two classical, broad categories are <b>taproot</b> and <b>fi=
brous</b> systems, but several specialised root types =E2=80=94 notably <b>=
adventitious</b>, <b>aerial</b>, <b>prop/stilt</b>, <b>climbing/adhesive</b=
>, <b>buttress</b>, <b>tuberous</b> (storage) and <b>floating</b> roots =E2=
=80=94 are biologically and ecologically important.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note=
-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Taproot_system">Taproot sys=
tem</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Taproot system"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>A taproot system is dominated by a single, vertically growing primary ro=
ot (the radicle) from which lateral roots arise. Taproots often function in=
 deep anchorage and in storage of carbohydrates and water (common in many d=
icotyledons and some biennials/perennials). Examples include carrot (Daucus=
 carota), dandelion (Taraxacum) and many true dicots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_no=
te-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fibrous_root_system">Fibrou=
s root system</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Fibrous r=
oot system"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>A fibrous root system consists of numerous, similarly sized roots that f=
orm a dense network near the soil surface. In many species this network is =
composed largely of adventitious roots that arise from the stem base rather=
 than the primary radicle. Fibrous systems are effective at soil binding, r=
apid uptake of surface nutrients and erosion control. Typical examples are =
grasses (Poaceae), wheat and rice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Adventitious_roots">Adventi=
tious roots</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Root&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Adventitious=
 roots"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>Adventitious roots arise from non-root organs (stems, nodes, leaves or c=
allus tissue) and play multiple roles: replacing or supplementing the prima=
ry root, providing mechanical support, enabling vegetative propagation, and=
 forming specialized root types (aerial roots, prop roots, pneumatophores).=
 They are especially important in monocots and many cultivated plants, and =
are a common response to wounding, flooding or other stressors.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ro=
ot#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Examples and notes: in many monocots the functional root system is a=
dventitious (forming a fibrous habit); maize (Zea mays) produces nodal brac=
e/prop roots that stabilise the stem; banyan (Ficus spp.) develops aerial a=
dventitious roots that may become supportive trunks; many cuttings root adv=
entitiously during vegetative propagation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-20"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Anatomy">Anatomy</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Anatomy"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:CSIRO_ScienceImage_11626_Barley_root.jpg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/9/96/CSIRO_ScienceImage_11626_Barley_root.jpg/250px-CSIRO_=
ScienceImage_11626_Barley_root.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"249" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1421" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"1417"></a><figcaption>The cross-section of a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Hordeum_vulgare" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hordeum vul=
gare">barley</a> root</figcaption></figure>
<p>Root morphology is divided into four zones: the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root_cap" title=3D"Root cap">root cap</a>, the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apical_meristem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Apical meristem">apical meristem</a>, the elongation zone, and the hair=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Okon1993_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Okon1993-21"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_cap" title=3D"Root cap">root cap</a>=
 of new roots helps the root penetrate the soil. These root caps are slough=
ed off as the root goes deeper creating a slimy surface that provides lubri=
cation. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meristem" title=3D"Mer=
istem">apical meristem</a> behind the root cap produces new root cells that=
 elongate. Then, root hairs form that absorb water and mineral nutrients fr=
om the soil.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-arizona_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-arizona-22"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e first root in seed producing plants is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Radicle" title=3D"Radicle">radicle</a>, which expands from the p=
lant embryo after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germination" tit=
le=3D"Germination">seed germination</a>.
</p><p>When dissected, the arrangement of the cells in a root is <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_hair" title=3D"Root hair">root hair</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidermis_(botany)" title=3D"Epi=
dermis (botany)">epidermis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ep=
iblem" title=3D"Epiblem">epiblem</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Cortex_(botany)" title=3D"Cortex (botany)">cortex</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endodermis" title=3D"Endodermis">endodermis</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pericycle" title=3D"Pericycle">peri=
cycle</a> and, lastly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vascula=
r_tissue" title=3D"Vascular tissue">vascular tissue</a> in the centre of a =
root to transport the water absorbed by the root to other places of the pla=
nt.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white=
-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Plea=
se_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"need diagram =
(March 2016)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ranunculus_Root_Cross_Section.png" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/9/9e/Ranunculus_Root_Cross_Section.png/250px-Ranunculus_Root_Cros=
s_Section.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"187" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"648" data-file-height=3D"485"></a><figcapt=
ion><i>Ranunculus</i> root cross section</figcaption></figure>
<p>Perhaps the most striking characteristic of roots that distinguishes the=
m from other plant organs such as stem-branches and leaves is that roots ha=
ve an <i>endogenous</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> origin, <i=
>i.e.</i>, they originate and develop from an inner layer of the mother axi=
s, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pericycle" title=3D"Per=
icycle">pericycle</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In contras=
t, stem-branches and leaves are <i>exogenous</i>, <i>i.e.</i>, they start t=
o develop from the cortex, an outer layer.
</p><p>In response to the concentration of nutrients, roots also synthesize=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cytokinin" title=3D"Cytokinin">cy=
tokinin</a>, which acts as a signal as to how fast the shoots can grow. Roo=
ts often function in storage of food and nutrients. The roots of most vascu=
lar plant species enter into symbiosis with certain <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fungi" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fungi">fungi</a> to=
 form <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycorrhiza" title=3D"Mycorrh=
iza">mycorrhizae</a>, and a large range of other organisms including <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteria" title=3D"Bacteria">bacteria</a=
> also closely associate with roots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-25"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kiental_entre_Herrsching_y_Andechs,_Alemania_=
2012-05-01,_DD_12.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Kiental_entre_Herrsching_y_=
Andechs%2C_Alemania_2012-05-01%2C_DD_12.JPG/250px-Kiental_entre_Herrsching_=
y_Andechs%2C_Alemania_2012-05-01%2C_DD_12.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"=
250" height=3D"185" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5071" data=
-file-height=3D"3744"></a><figcaption>Large, mature tree roots above the so=
il</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Root_system_architecture_(R=
SA)"><span id=3D"Root_system_architecture_.28RSA.29"></span>Root system arc=
hitecture (RSA)</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Root sy=
stem architecture (RSA)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tree_Roots_at_Riverside.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/4/4d/Tree_Roots_at_Riverside.jpg/250px-Tree_Roots_at_Riverside.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"2304" data-file-height=3D"1728"></a><figcaption>Tree roots a=
t <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cliffs_of_the_Neuse_State_Park" =
title=3D"Cliffs of the Neuse State Park">Cliffs of the Neuse State Park</a>=
</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In its simplest form, the term root system architecture (RSA) refers to =
the spatial configuration of a plant's root system. This system can be extr=
emely complex and is dependent upon multiple factors such as the species of=
 the plant itself, the composition of the soil and the availability of nutr=
ients.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Root architecture plays the =
important role of providing a secure supply of nutrients and water as well =
as anchorage and support.
</p><p>The configuration of root systems serves to structurally support the=
 plant and compete with other plants for uptake of nutrients within the soi=
l.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:0-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Roots grow <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_phenotypic_plasticity" title=3D"Root pheno=
typic plasticity">in response to</a> specific ecological conditions, which,=
 if changed, can impede a plant's growth. For example, a root system that h=
as developed in dry soil may not be as efficient in flooded soil, yet plant=
s are able to adapt to other changes in the environment, such as seasonal c=
hanges.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:0-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Terms_and_components">Terms=
 and components</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Terms a=
nd components"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>The main terms used to classify the architecture of a root system are:<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Fitter_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Fitter-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">

<tbody><tr>
<td>Branch magnitude</td>
<td>Number of links (exterior or interior)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Topology</td>
<td>Pattern of branching (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herringb=
one_pattern" title=3D"Herringbone pattern">Herringbone</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dichotomous" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dicho=
tomous">Dichotomous</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_sy=
mmetry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radial symmetry">Radial</a>)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Link length</td>
<td>Distance between branches
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Root angle</td>
<td>Radial angle of a lateral root's base around the parent root's circumfe=
rence, the angle of a lateral root from its parent root, and the angle an e=
ntire system spreads.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Link radius</td>
<td>Diameter of root
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>All components of the root architecture are regulated through a complex =
interaction between genetic responses and responses due to environmental st=
imuli. These developmental stimuli are categorized as intrinsic, the geneti=
c and nutritional influences, or extrinsic, the environmental influences, a=
nd are interpreted by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_trans=
duction_pathways" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Signal transduction pathwa=
ys">signal transduction pathways</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Malamy_29-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Mala=
my-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Extrinsic factors affecting root architecture include <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitropism" title=3D"Gravitropism">gravity</a>=
, light exposure, water and oxygen, as well as the availability or lack of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nitrogen" title=3D"Nitrogen">nitro=
gen</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phosphorus" title=3D"Phos=
phorus">phosphorus</a>, sulphur, aluminium and sodium chloride. The main ho=
rmones (intrinsic stimuli) and respective pathways responsible for root arc=
hitecture development include:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">

<tbody><tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auxin" title=3D"Auxin">Auxin</=
a></td>
<td>Lateral root formation, maintenance of apical dominance and <a rel=3D"n=
ofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://academic.oup.com/plphys/ar=
ticle/170/2/603/6114063">adventitious</a> root formation.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cytokinins" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Cytokinins">Cytokinins</a></td>
<td>Cytokinins regulate root apical meristem size and promote lateral root =
elongation.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethylene" title=3D"Ethylene">E=
thylene</a></td>
<td>Promotes crown root formation.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibberellins" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Gibberellins">Gibberellins</a></td>
<td>Together with ethylene, they promote crown primordia growth and elongat=
ion. Together with auxin, they promote root elongation. Gibberellins also i=
nhibit lateral root primordia initiation.
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Growth">Growth</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Growth"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Root_of_a_Tree.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/=
Root_of_a_Tree.JPG/250px-Root_of_a_Tree.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"25=
0" height=3D"342" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1211" data-f=
ile-height=3D"1658"></a><figcaption>Roots of trees</figcaption></figure>
<p>Early root growth is one of the functions of the <b>apical meristem</b> =
located near the tip of the root. The meristem cells more or less continuou=
sly divide, producing more meristem, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Root_cap" title=3D"Root cap">root cap</a> cells (these are sacrificed to=
 protect the meristem), and undifferentiated root cells. The latter become =
the primary tissues of the root, first undergoing elongation, a process tha=
t pushes the root tip forward in the growing medium. Gradually these cells =
differentiate and mature into specialized cells of the root tissues.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Russell_Hertz_McMillan_2013_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Russell_Hertz_McMillan_201=
3-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Growth from apical meristems is known as <b>primary growth</b>, whic=
h encompasses all elongation.
<b>Secondary growth</b> encompasses all growth in diameter, a major compone=
nt of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woody_plant" title=3D"Woody =
plant">woody plant</a> tissues and many nonwoody plants. For example, stora=
ge roots of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweet_potato" title=3D=
"Sweet potato">sweet potato</a> have secondary growth but are not woody. Se=
condary growth occurs at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Later=
al_meristem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lateral meristem">lateral meris=
tems</a>, namely the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vascular_camb=
ium" title=3D"Vascular cambium">vascular cambium</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cork_cambium" title=3D"Cork cambium">cork cambium</a=
>. The former forms <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secondary_xyle=
m" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Secondary xylem">secondary xylem</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secondary_phloem" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Secondary phloem">secondary phloem</a>, while the latter for=
ms the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periderm" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Periderm">periderm</a>.
</p><p>In plants with secondary growth, the vascular cambium, originating b=
etween the xylem and the phloem, forms a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (geomet=
ry)">cylinder</a> of tissue along the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Plant_stem" title=3D"Plant stem">stem</a> and root.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_=
note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> The vascular cambium forms new cells on both the insid=
e and outside of the cambium cylinder, with those on the inside forming sec=
ondary xylem cells, and those on the outside forming secondary phloem cells=
. As secondary xylem accumulates, the "girth" (lateral dimensions) of the s=
tem and root increases. As a result, tissues beyond the secondary phloem in=
cluding the epidermis and cortex, in many cases tend to be pushed outward a=
nd are eventually "sloughed off" (shed).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-32"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>At this point, the cork cambium begins to form the periderm, consist=
ing of protective <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cork_(material)"=
 title=3D"Cork (material)">cork</a> cells. The walls of cork cells contains=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suberin" title=3D"Suberin">suberi=
n</a> thickenings, which is an extra cellular complex biopolymer.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Root#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The suberin thickenings functions by providi=
ng a physical barrier, protection against pathogens and by preventing water=
 loss from the surrounding tissues. In addition, it also aids the process o=
f wound healing in plants.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is al=
so postulated that suberin could be a component of the apoplastic barrier (=
present at the outer cell layers of roots) which prevents toxic compounds f=
rom entering the root and reduces radial oxygen loss (ROL) from the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerenchyma" title=3D"Aerenchyma">aerenchy=
ma</a> during waterlogging.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ReferenceA_35-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-ReferenceA=
-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In roots, the cork cambium originates in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pericycle" title=3D"Pericycle">pericycle</a>, a=
 component of the vascular cylinder.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ReferenceA_35-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-R=
eferenceA-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The vascular cambium produces new layers of secondary xylem annually=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The xylem vessels are dead at mat=
urity (in some) but are responsible for most water transport through the va=
scular tissue in stems and roots.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tree_branches_and_roots.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/c=
ommons/thumb/4/4c/Tree_branches_and_roots.jpg/250px-Tree_branches_and_roots=
.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"333" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"750" data-file-height=3D"1000"></a><figcaption>Tree=
 roots at Port Jackson</figcaption></figure>
<p>Tree roots usually grow to three times the diameter of the branch spread=
, only half of which lie underneath the trunk and canopy. The roots from on=
e side of a tree usually supply nutrients to the foliage on the same side. =
Some families however, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sap=
indaceae" title=3D"Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</a> (the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple" title=3D"Maple">maple</a> family), show no correl=
ation between root location and where the root supplies nutrients on the pl=
ant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Regulation">Regulation</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Regulation"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is a correlation of roots using the process of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plant_perception_(physiology)" title=3D"Plant percept=
ion (physiology)">plant perception</a> to sense their physical environment =
to grow,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> including the sensing of l=
ight,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and physical barriers. Plants=
 also sense gravity and respond through auxin pathways,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_=
note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> resulting in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gravitropism" title=3D"Gravitropism">gravitropism</a>. Over time, roots can=
 crack foundations, snap water lines, and lift sidewalks. Research has show=
n that roots have ability to recognize 'self' and 'non-self' roots in same =
soil environment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The correct environment of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Aeration" title=3D"Aeration">air</a>, mineral <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Nutrients" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nutrients">nutrients<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water" title=3D"Water">wat=
er</a> directs plant roots to grow in any direction to meet the plant's nee=
ds. Roots will shy or shrink away from dry<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-42"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> or other poor soil conditions.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitropism" title=3D"Grav=
itropism">Gravitropism</a> directs roots to grow downward at <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germination" title=3D"Germination">germination</=
a>, the growth mechanism of plants that also causes the shoot to grow upwar=
d.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Different types of roots such as primary, seminal, lateral and crown are ma=
intained at different gravitropic setpoint angles i.e. the direction in whi=
ch they grow. Recent research show that root angle in cereal crops such as =
barley and wheat is regulated by a novel gene called Enhanced Gravitropism =
1 (EGT1).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Research indicates that plant roots growing in search of productive =
nutrition can sense and avoid soil compaction through diffusion of the gas =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethylene" title=3D"Ethylene">ethyl=
ene</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:ArabidopsisLatRoot.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d=
/df/ArabidopsisLatRoot.jpg/250px-ArabidopsisLatRoot.jpg" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"239" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
618" data-file-height=3D"592"></a><figcaption>Fluorescent imaging of an eme=
rging lateral root</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Shade_avoidance_response">S=
hade avoidance response</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Shade avoidance response"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In order to avoid shade, plants utilize a shade avoidance response. When=
 a plant is under dense vegetation, the presence of other vegetation nearby=
 will cause the plant to avoid lateral growth and experience an increase in=
 upward shoot, as well as downward root growth. In order to escape shade, p=
lants adjust their root architecture, most notably by decreasing the length=
 and amount of lateral roots emerging from the primary root. Experimentatio=
n of mutant variants of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabido=
psis_thaliana" title=3D"Arabidopsis thaliana">Arabidopsis thaliana</a></i> =
found that plants sense the Red to Far Red light ratio that enters the plan=
t through photoreceptors known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Phytochrome" title=3D"Phytochrome">phytochromes</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:02=
_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#ci=
te_note-:02-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Nearby plant leaves will absorb red light and r=
eflect far-red light, which will cause the ratio red to far red light to lo=
wer. The phytochrome PhyA that senses this Red to Far Red light ratio is lo=
calized in both the root system as well as the shoot system of plants, but =
through knockout mutant experimentation, it was found that root localized P=
hyA does not sense the light ratio, whether directly or axially, that leads=
 to changes in the lateral root architecture.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:02_46-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note=
-:02-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Research instead found that shoot localized PhyA is th=
e phytochrome responsible for causing these architectural changes of the la=
teral root. Research has also found that phytochrome completes these archit=
ectural changes through the manipulation of auxin distribution in the root =
of the plant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:02_46-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:02-46"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When a low =
enough Red to Far Red ratio is sensed by PhyA, the phyA in the shoot will b=
e mostly in its active form.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_47-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:1-47"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In this form, PhyA stabilize the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Transcription_factor" title=3D"Transcription factor">transcription factor<=
/a> HY5 causing it to no longer be degraded as it is when phyA is in its in=
active form. This stabilized transcription factor is then able to be transp=
orted to the roots of the plant through the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Phloem" title=3D"Phloem">phloem</a>, where it proceeds to induce =
its own transcription as a way to amplify its signal. In the roots of the p=
lant HY5 functions to inhibit an auxin response factor known as ARF19, a re=
sponse factor responsible for the translation of PIN3 and LAX3, two well kn=
own auxin transporting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein" ti=
tle=3D"Protein">proteins</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_47-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:1-47"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Thus, through manipulation of ARF19, the level and activity of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auxin" title=3D"Auxin">auxin</a> transpor=
ters PIN3 and LAX3 is inhibited.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_47-2" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:1-47"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Once inhibited, auxin levels will be low in areas where lateral root =
emergence normally occurs, resulting in a failure for the plant to have the=
 emergence of the lateral root primordium through the root <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pericycle" title=3D"Pericycle">pericycle</a>. With=
 this complex manipulation of Auxin transport in the roots, lateral root em=
ergence will be inhibited in the roots and the root will instead elongate d=
ownwards, promoting vertical plant growth in an attempt to avoid shade.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-:02_46-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:02-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_47-3" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note=
-:1-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Research of Arabidopsis has led to the discovery of how this auxin m=
ediated root response works. In an attempt to discover the role that <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phytochrome" title=3D"Phytochrome">phyto=
chrome</a> plays in lateral root development, Salisbury et al. (2007) worke=
d with <i>Arabidopsis thaliana</i> grown on agar plates. Salisbury et al. u=
sed wild type plants along with varying protein knockout and gene knockout =
Arabidopsis mutants to observe the results these mutations had on the root =
architecture, protein presence, and gene expression. To do this, Salisbury =
et al. used GFP fluorescence along with other forms of both macro and micro=
scopic imagery to observe any changes various mutations caused. From these =
research, Salisbury et al. were able to theorize that shoot located phytoch=
romes alter auxin levels in roots, controlling lateral root development and=
 overall root architecture.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:02_46-4" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:02-46"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> In the experiments of van Gelderen et al. (2018), they wanted to see if =
and how it is that the shoot of <i>A.&nbsp;thaliana</i> alters and affects =
root development and root architecture. To do this, they took <i>Arabidopsi=
s</i> plants, grew them in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agar" t=
itle=3D"Agar">agar gel</a>, and exposed the roots and shoots to separate so=
urces of light. From here, they altered the different wavelengths of light =
the shoot and root of the plants were receiving and recorded the lateral ro=
ot density, amount of lateral roots, and the general architecture of the la=
teral roots. To identify the function of specific photoreceptors, proteins,=
 genes, and hormones, they utilized various <i>Arabidopsis</i> knockout mut=
ants and observed the resulting changes in lateral roots architecture. Thro=
ugh their observations and various experiments, van Gelderen et al. were ab=
le to develop a mechanism for how root detection of Red to Far-red light ra=
tios alter lateral root development.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_47-4" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:1-47"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types">Types</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Types"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
