<p>The roots, or parts of roots, of many plant species have become speciali=
zed to serve adaptive purposes besides the two primary functions<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap=
;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" t=
itle=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"there's no intro section (=
March 2016)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>, described in the i=
ntroduction.
</p>
<ul><li><b>Adventitious roots</b> arise out-of-sequence from the more usual=
 root formation of branches of a primary root, and instead originate from t=
he stem, branches, leaves, or old woody roots. They commonly occur in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monocot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Monocot">monocots</a> and pteridophytes, but also in many <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dicot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dicot">dicot=
s</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clover" title=3D"Cl=
over">clover</a> (<i>Trifolium</i>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ivy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ivy">ivy</a> (<i>Hedera</i>), <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strawberry" title=3D"Strawberry">strawbe=
rry</a> (<i>Fragaria</i>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will=
ow" title=3D"Willow">willow</a> (<i>Salix</i>). Most aerial roots and stilt=
 roots are adventitious. In some conifers adventitious roots can form the l=
argest part of the root system. Adventitious root formation is enhanced in =
many plant species during (partial) submergence, to increase gas exchange a=
nd storage of gases like oxygen.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-48"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Di=
stinct types of adventitious roots can be classified and are dependent on m=
orphology, growth dynamics and function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-49"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><b>Aerating roots</b> (or <b>knee root</b> or <b>knee</b> or <b>pneumat=
ophores</b>): roots rising above the ground, especially above water such as=
 in some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangrove" title=3D"Mangro=
ve">mangrove</a> genera (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avicen=
nia" title=3D"Avicennia">Avicennia</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sonneratia" title=3D"Sonneratia">Sonneratia</a></i>). In some plants =
like <i>Avicennia</i> the erect roots have a large number of breathing pore=
s for exchange of gases.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerial_roots" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Aerial roots">Aerial roots</a></b>: roots entirely above =
the ground, such as in ivy (<i>Hedera</i>) or in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Epiphyte" title=3D"Epiphyte">epiphytic</a> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orchid" title=3D"Orchid">orchids</a>. Many aerial r=
oots are used to receive water and nutrient intake directly from the air =
=E2=80=93 from fogs, dew or humidity in the air.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-deficit=
_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#ci=
te_note-deficit-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some rely on leaf systems to gather rain or=
 humidity and even store it in scales or pockets. Other aerial roots, such =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangrove" title=3D"Mangrove">ma=
ngrove</a> aerial roots, are used for aeration and not for water absorption=
. Other aerial roots are used mainly for structure, functioning as prop roo=
ts, as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maize" title=3D"Maize">m=
aize</a> or anchor roots or as the trunk in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Strangler_fig" title=3D"Strangler fig">strangler fig</a>. In some=
 Epiphytes =E2=80=93 plants living above the surface on other plants, aeria=
l roots serve for reaching to water sources or reaching the surface, and th=
en functioning as regular surface roots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-deficit_51-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-=
deficit-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canopy_root" title=3D"Canop=
y root">Canopy roots</a>/arboreal roots</b>: roots that form when tree bran=
ches support mats of epiphytes and detritus, which hold water and nutrients=
 in the canopy. They grow out into these mats, likely to utilize the availa=
ble nutrients and moisture.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><b>Coarse roots</b>: roots that have undergone secondary thickening and=
 have a woody structure. These roots have some ability to absorb water and =
nutrients, but their main function is transport and to provide a structure =
to connect the smaller diameter, fine roots to the rest of the plant.</li>
<li><b>Contractile roots</b>: roots that pull bulbs or corms of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monocot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Monoc=
ot">monocots</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyacinth=
_(plant)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyacinth (plant)">hyacinth</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lily" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Lily">lily</a>, and some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tapro=
ot" title=3D"Taproot">taproots</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Dandelion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dandelion">dandelion</a=
>, deeper in the soil through expanding radially and contracting longitudin=
ally. They have a wrinkled surface.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-53"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</li>
<li><b>Coralloid roots</b>: similar to root nodules, these provide nitrogen=
 to the plant. They are often larger than nodules, branched, and located at=
 or near the soil surface, and harbor nitrogen-fixing <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyanobacteria" title=3D"Cyanobacteria">cyanobacteria</a=
>. They are only found in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cycad" t=
itle=3D"Cycad">cycads</a>.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimorphic_root_system" titl=
e=3D"Dimorphic root system">Dimorphic root systems</a></b>: roots with two =
distinctive forms for two separate functions</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fine_root" title=3D"Fine ro=
ot">Fine roots</a></b>: typically primary roots &lt;2&nbsp;mm diameter that=
 have the function of water and nutrient uptake. They are often heavily bra=
nched and support mycorrhizas. These roots may be short lived, but are repl=
aced by the plant in an ongoing process of root 'turnover'.</li>
<li><b>Haustorial roots</b>: roots of parasitic plants that can absorb wate=
r and nutrients from another plant, such as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Mistletoe" title=3D"Mistletoe">mistletoe</a> (<i>Viscum album<=
/i>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodder" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Dodder">dodder</a>.</li>
<li><b>Propagative roots</b>: roots that form adventitious buds that develo=
p into aboveground shoots, termed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Basal_shoot" title=3D"Basal shoot">suckers</a>, which form new plants, as i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asclepias_syriaca" title=3D"Ascl=
epias syriaca">common milkweed (<i>Asclepias syriaca</i>)</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cirsium_arvense" title=3D"Cirsium arvense">Can=
ada thistle (<i>Cirsium arvense</i>)</a>, and many others.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#ci=
te_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><b>Photosynthetic roots</b>: roots that are green and photosynthesize, =
providing sugar to the plant. They are similar to <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Phylloclade" title=3D"Phylloclade">phylloclades</a>. Severa=
l orchids have these, such as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
endrophylax" title=3D"Dendrophylax">Dendrophylax</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taeniophyllum" title=3D"Taeniophyllum">Taenio=
phyllum</a></i>.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proteoid_root" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Proteoid root">Proteoid roots</a></b> or cluster roots: =
dense clusters of rootlets of limited growth that develop under low <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phosphate" title=3D"Phosphate">phosphate<=
/a> or low <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron" title=3D"Iron">ir=
on</a> conditions in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proteaceae" t=
itle=3D"Proteaceae">Proteaceae</a> and some plants from the following famil=
ies <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betulaceae" title=3D"Betulacea=
e">Betulaceae</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casuarinaceae" =
title=3D"Casuarinaceae">Casuarinaceae</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Elaeagnaceae" title=3D"Elaeagnaceae">Elaeagnaceae</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moraceae" title=3D"Moraceae">Moraceae</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fabaceae" title=3D"Fabaceae">Fabacea=
e</a> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myricaceae" title=3D"=
Myricaceae">Myricaceae</a></i>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_nodule" title=3D"Root nod=
ule"><b>Root nodules</b></a>: roots that harbor nitrogen-fixing soil bacter=
ia. These are often very short and rounded. Root nodules are found in virtu=
ally all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legume" title=3D"Legume">=
legumes</a>.</li>
<li><b>Stilt roots</b>: adventitious support roots, common among <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangrove" title=3D"Mangrove">mangroves</a>. =
They grow down from lateral branches, branching in the soil.</li>
<li><b>Storage roots</b>: roots modified for storage of food or water, such=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrot" title=3D"Carrot">carro=
ts</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beet" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Beet">beets</a>. They include some <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Taproot" title=3D"Taproot">taproots</a> and tuberous roots.<=
/li>
<li><b>Structural roots</b>: large roots that have undergone considerable s=
econdary thickening and provide mechanical support to woody plants and tree=
s.</li>
<li><b>Surface roots</b>: roots that proliferate close below the soil surfa=
ce, exploiting water and easily available nutrients. Where conditions are c=
lose to optimum in the surface layers of soil, the growth of surface roots =
is encouraged and they commonly become the dominant roots.</li>
<li><b>Tuberous roots</b>: fleshy and enlarged lateral roots for food or wa=
ter storage, e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweet_potato" ti=
tle=3D"Sweet potato">sweet potato</a>. A type of storage root distinct from=
 taproot.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Depths">Depths</h2><span cl=
