<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Evolutionary_history">Evolu=
tionary history</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Evoluti=
onary history"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_=
plants#Evolution_of_roots" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Evolution of plan=
ts">Evolution of plants =C2=A7&nbsp;Evolution of roots</a></div>
<p>The fossil record of roots=E2=80=94or rather, infilled voids where roots=
 rotted after death=E2=80=94spans back to the late <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Silurian" title=3D"Silurian">Silurian</a>, about 430&nbsp;=
million years ago.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Retallack1986_57-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Retallack1986-57=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> Their identification is difficult, because casts and molds of=
 roots are so similar in appearance to animal burrows. They can be discrimi=
nated using a range of features.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hillier2008_58-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Hill=
ier2008-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The evolutionary development of roots likely happen=
ed from the modification of shallow <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Rhizomes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rhizomes">rhizomes</a> (modified=
 horizontal stems) which anchored primitive vascular plants combined with t=
he development of filamentous outgrowths (called <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Rhizoid" title=3D"Rhizoid">rhizoids</a>) which anchored the =
plants and conducted water to the plant from the soil.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5=
9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_n=
ote-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Environmental_interactions"=
>Environmental interactions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Environmental interactions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cycas_revoluta_coralloid_roots.JPG" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/9/9a/Cycas_revoluta_coralloid_roots.JPG/250px-Cycas_revoluta_cor=
alloid_roots.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"167" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2899" data-file-height=3D"1933"></a><fi=
gcaption>Coralloid roots of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyc=
as_revoluta" title=3D"Cycas revoluta">Cycas revoluta</a></i></figcaption></=
figure>
<p>Light has been shown to have some impact on roots, but it's not been stu=
died as much as the effect of light on other plant systems. Early research =
in the 1930s found that light decreased the effectiveness of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indole-3-acetic_acid" title=3D"Indole-3-acetic a=
cid">Indole-3-acetic acid</a> on adventitious root initiation. Studies of t=
he pea in the 1950s shows that lateral root formation was inhibited by ligh=
t, and in the early 1960s researchers found that light could induce positiv=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitropic" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Gravitropic">gravitropic</a> responses in some situations. The =
effects of light on root elongation has been studied for <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monocotyledonous" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mon=
ocotyledonous">monocotyledonous</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dicotyledonous" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dicotyledonous">dicoty=
ledonous</a> plants, with the majority of studies finding that light inhibi=
ted root elongation, whether pulsed or continuous. Studies of <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabidopsis" title=3D"Arabidopsis">Arabidops=
is</a></i> in the 1990s showed negative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Phototropism" title=3D"Phototropism">phototropism</a> and inhibition =
of the elongation of root hairs in light sensed by <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/PhyB" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"PhyB">phyB</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-jpp1997_60-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-jpp1997-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Certain plants, namely <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faba=
ceae" title=3D"Fabaceae">Fabaceae</a>, form <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Root_nodules" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root nodules">root n=
odules</a> in order to associate and form a symbiotic relationship with nit=
rogen-fixing bacteria called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhizo=
bia" title=3D"Rhizobia">rhizobia</a>. Owing to the high energy required to =
fix nitrogen from the atmosphere, the bacteria take carbon compounds from t=
he plant to fuel the process. In return, the plant takes nitrogen compounds=
 produced from ammonia by the bacteria.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-61"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Soil temperature is a factor that effects <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoot_initiation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=
=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Root initiation (page does not exist)">root in=
itiation</a> and length. Root length is usually impacted more dramatically =
by temperature than overall mass, where cooler temperatures tend to cause m=
ore lateral growth because downward extension is limited by cooler temperat=
ures at subsoil levels. Needs vary by plant species, but in temperate regio=
ns cool temperatures may limit root systems. Cool temperature species like =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oats" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Oats">oats</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rapeseed" titl=
e=3D"Rapeseed">rapeseed</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rye" =
title=3D"Rye">rye</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheat" titl=
e=3D"Wheat">wheat</a> fare better in lower temperatures than summer <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annual_plant" title=3D"Annual plant">annu=
als</a> like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maize" title=3D"Maize=
">maize</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotton" title=3D"C=
otton">cotton</a>. Researchers have found that plants like cotton develop w=
ider and shorter <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taproot" title=3D=
"Taproot">taproots</a> in cooler temperatures. The first root originating f=
rom the seed usually has a wider diameter than root branches, so smaller ro=
ot diameters are expected if temperatures increase root initiation. Root di=
ameter also decreases when the root elongates.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-encyclope=
dia_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root=
#cite_note-encyclopedia-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Plant_interactions">Plant i=
nteractions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Root&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Plant inter=
actions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>Plants can interact with one another in their environment through their =
root systems. Studies have demonstrated that plant-plant interaction occurs=
 among root systems via the soil as a medium. Researchers have tested wheth=
er plants growing in ambient conditions would change their behavior if a ne=
arby plant was exposed to drought conditions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_63-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-=
:2-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
Since nearby plants showed no changes in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Stoma" title=3D"Stoma">stomatal</a> aperture researchers believe the=
 drought signal spread through the roots and soil, not through the air as a=
 volatile chemical signal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_64-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-:3-64"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Soil_interactions">Soil int=
eractions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRo=
ot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Soil interact=
ions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>Soil microbiota can suppress both disease and beneficial root symbionts =
(mycorrhizal fungi are easier to establish in sterile soil). Inoculation wi=
th soil bacteria can increase internode extension, yield and quicken flower=
ing. The migration of bacteria along the root varies with natural soil cond=
itions. For example, research has found that the root systems of wheat seed=
s inoculated with <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azotobacter" =
title=3D"Azotobacter">Azotobacter</a></i> showed higher populations in soil=
s favorable to <i>Azotobacter</i> growth. Some studies have been unsuccessf=
ul in increasing the levels of certain microbes (such as <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P._fluorescens" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P.=
 fluorescens">P.&nbsp;fluorescens</a></i>) in natural soil without prior st=
erilization.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bowen_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-Bowen-65"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Grass root systems are beneficial at reducing <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_erosion" title=3D"Soil erosion">soil erosion</a> by=
 holding the soil together. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perenn=
ial" title=3D"Perennial">Perennial</a> grasses that grow wild in rangelands=
 contribute organic matter to the soil when their old roots decay after att=
acks by beneficial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungi" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fungi">fungi</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Protozoa" title=3D"Protozoa">protozoa</a>, bacteria, insects and wor=
ms release nutrients.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-arizona_22-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-arizona-22"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Scientists have observed significant diversity of the microbial cove=
r of roots at around 10 percent of three week old root segments covered. On=
 younger roots there was even low coverage, but even on 3-month-old roots t=
he coverage was only around 37%. Before the 1970s, scientists believed that=
 the majority of the root surface was covered by microorganisms.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-arizona_22-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Root#cite_note-arizona-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Nutrient_absorption">Nutrie=
nt absorption</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Nutrient=
 absorption"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>Researchers studying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maize" tit=
le=3D"Maize">maize</a> seedlings found that calcium absorption was greatest=
 in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apical_meristem" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Apical meristem">apical</a> root segment, and potassi=
um at the base of the root. Along other root segments absorption was simila=
r. Absorbed potassium is transported to the root tip, and to a lesser exten=
t other parts of the root, then also to the shoot and grain. Calcium transp=
ort from the apical segment is slower, mostly transported upward and accumu=
lated in stem and shoot.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Researchers found that partial deficiencies of K or P did not change=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatty_acid" title=3D"Fatty ac=
id">fatty acid</a> composition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Phosphatidyl_choline" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Phosphatidyl choline">=
phosphatidyl choline</a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bra=
ssica_napus_L." class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Brassica napus L.">Brassica =
napus L.</a></i> plants. Calcium deficiency did, on the other hand, lead to=
 a marked decline of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyunsaturat=
ed" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polyunsaturated">polyunsaturated</a> com=
pounds that would be expected to have negative impacts for integrity of the=
 plant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Membrane" title=3D"Membrane=
">membrane</a>, that could effect some properties like its permeability, an=
d is needed for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion" title=3D"=
Ion">ion</a> uptake activity of the root membranes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note=
-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Economic_importance">Econom=
ic importance</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRoot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Economic=
 importance"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Roots_and_Soil_Erosion.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/a/a9/Roots_and_Soil_Erosion.jpg/250px-Roots_and_Soil_Erosion.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"166" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"2048" data-file-height=3D"1360"></a><figcaption>Roots can also =
protect the environment by holding the soil to reduce soil erosion.</figcap=
tion></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:World_Primary_Crops_Harvested_Area_By_Commodi=
ty_Group.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wiki=
media.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/World_Primary_Crops_Harvested_Area_B=
y_Commodity_Group.svg/250px-World_Primary_Crops_Harvested_Area_By_Commodity=
_Group.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"209" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"428"></a><figcap=
tion>Roots and tubers are some of the most widely harvested crops in the wo=
rld.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_crop" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Root crop">root crops</a> refers to any edible undergro=
und plant structure, but many root crops are actually stems, such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potato" title=3D"Potato">potato</a> tube=
rs. Edible roots include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cassava" =
title=3D"Cassava">cassava</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swe=
et_potato" title=3D"Sweet potato">sweet potato</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Beet" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Beet">beet</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrot" title=3D"Carrot">carrot</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutabaga" title=3D"Rutabaga">rutaba=
ga</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turnip" title=3D"Turnip">t=
urnip</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parsnip" title=3D"Parsn=
ip">parsnip</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radish" title=3D"=
Radish">radish</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yam_(vegetable=
)" title=3D"Yam (vegetable)">yam</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Horseradish" title=3D"Horseradish">horseradish</a>. Spices obtained =
from roots include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sassafras" titl=
e=3D"Sassafras">sassafras</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ang=
elica" title=3D"Angelica">angelica</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Smilax_regelii" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Smilax regelii">sarsap=
arilla</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Licorice" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Licorice">licorice</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sugar_beet" title=3D"Sugar =
beet">Sugar beet</a> is an important source of sugar. <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yam_(vegetable)" title=3D"Yam (vegetable)">Yam</a> root=
s are a source of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estrogen" title=
=3D"Estrogen">estrogen</a> compounds used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Birth_control_pill" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Birth control=
 pill">birth control pills</a>. The fish <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Poison" title=3D"Poison">poison</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Insecticide" title=3D"Insecticide">insecticide</a> <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotenone" title=3D"Rotenone">rotenone</a> is =
obtained from roots of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonchoca=
rpus" title=3D"Lonchocarpus">Lonchocarpus</a></i> spp. Important medicines =
from roots are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ginseng" title=3D"G=
inseng">ginseng</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aconitum" tit=
le=3D"Aconitum">aconite</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syrup=
_of_ipecac" title=3D"Syrup of ipecac">ipecac</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gentian" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gentian">gentian</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reserpine" title=3D"Reserpin=
e">reserpine</a>. Several legumes that have nitrogen-fixing root nodules ar=
e used as green manure crops, which provide nitrogen fertilizer for other c=
rops when plowed under. Specialized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Bald_cypress" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bald cypress">bald cypress</=
a> roots, termed knees, are sold as souvenirs, lamp bases and carved into f=
olk art. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_the=
_Americas" title=3D"Indigenous peoples of the Americas">Native Americans</a=
> used the flexible roots of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picea=
_glauca" title=3D"Picea glauca">white spruce</a> for basketry.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree" title=3D"Tree">Tree</=
a> roots can heave and destroy <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Con=
crete" title=3D"Concrete">concrete</a> sidewalks and crush or clog buried p=
ipes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Root#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The aerial roots of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strangler_fig" title=3D"Strangler fig">st=
rangler fig</a> have damaged ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Maya_architecture" title=3D"Maya architecture">Mayan</a> <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temple" title=3D"Temple">temples</a> in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_America" title=3D"Central America=
">Central America</a> and the temple of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Angkor_Wat" title=3D"Angkor Wat">Angkor Wat</a> in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambodia" title=3D"Cambodia">Cambodia</a>.
</p><p>Trees stabilize soil on a slope prone to <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Landslides" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Landslides">landsl=
ides</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_hair" title=3D"=
Root hair">root hairs</a> work as an anchor on the soil.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vegetative_propagation" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vegetative propagation">Vegetative propagation<=
/a> of plants via cuttings depends on adventitious root formation. Hundreds=
 of millions of plants are propagated via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Cuttings_(plants)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cuttings (plants)=
">cuttings</a> annually including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Chrysanthemum" title=3D"Chrysanthemum">chrysanthemum</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poinsettia" title=3D"Poinsettia">poinsettia</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carnation" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Carnation">carnation</a>, ornamental <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Shrub" title=3D"Shrub">shrubs</a> and many <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Houseplants" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Houseplants">=
houseplants</a>.
</p><p>Roots can also protect the environment by holding the soil to reduce=
 soil erosion. This is especially important in areas such as <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sand_dunes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sand =
dunes">sand dunes</a>.
</p>
